{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 09:31:45.254471", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Network troubleshooting diagnosis report\n\nScope and objective\n- Verify end-to-end health of an OSPF-based enterprise network providing HTTP services via web servers and an Nginx load balancer, with DNS in 10.200.0.0/24 and DHCP for host subnets.\n- Focus on anomaly detection, fault localization, and root-cause identification. No remediation is proposed here.\n\nExecutive summary\n- Routing, IP connectivity, DHCP, and HTTP services (by IP) are healthy.\n- The DNS service is not functioning: name resolution for local FQDNs (e.g., web0.local, web99.local) fails from hosts and even on the DNS server itself.\n- Root cause: DNS daemon not running/not listening on dns_server (10.200.0.2), causing inability to resolve local names; thus, FQDN-based access to services fails even though IP connectivity and services are up.\n\nFindings and evidence\n\nControl-plane and L3 reachability\n- OSPF health:\n  - All routers show Full adjacencies: core routers, both distribution routers, and server_access_router report Full neighbors (functions.frr_exec “show ip ospf neighbor” on router_core_1/2/3, router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1, server_access_router).\n  - Server access router routing table includes:\n    - Connected 10.200.0.0/24 on br0, and OSPF-learned host subnets 10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24 via core_3 (functions.frr_show_ip_route on server_access_router).\n- End-to-end ICMP reachability:\n  - Hosts can ping server farm nodes and DHCP/DNS with low RTT, 0% loss (functions.get_reachability; additional pings from hosts to load_balancer and dhcp_server succeeded).\n- Host IP configuration and default routes:\n  - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.10/24 via 10.1.1.1 (DHCP assigned).\n  - host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.10/24 via 10.2.1.1 (DHCP assigned).\n  - DHCP server reachable from both hosts with low RTT (functions.ping_pair outputs).\n- Backend isolation:\n  - The load balancer has a secondary interface 20.200.0.1/24 toward its backend. 20.200.0.0/24 is not present in server_access_router route table; hence backends are not routable from host subnets (as designed).\n\nApplication-plane (HTTP) checks\n- Web servers (web_server_0..3) and load_balancer listen on TCP/80 (functions.netstat on each shows 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN).\n- HTTP by IP succeeds with HTTP 200:\n  - From both hosts: curl to http://10.200.0.3 (web_server_0) and http://10.200.0.7 (load_balancer) returns 200 (functions.exec_shell outputs).\n- HTTP by FQDN fails:\n  - From both hosts: curl -I http://web0.local and http://web99.local produce no output; curl -w %{http_code} shows 000 (functions.exec_shell), indicating connection not established due to name resolution failure.\n\nDNS subsystem\n- Hosts are configured to use dns_server (10.200.0.2) for DNS:\n  - /etc/resolv.conf on both hosts: nameserver 10.200.0.2.\n- Name resolution fails on hosts:\n  - getent hosts web99.local and web0.local return no records on both hosts (functions.exec_shell).\n- DNS server process not listening:\n  - On dns_server, netstat shows no process bound to UDP/TCP port 53; only docker’s 127.0.0.11 ephemeral services are present (functions.netstat on dns_server).\n- Even on the dns_server itself, local queries fail:\n  - host/nslookup web0.local and web99.local show “no servers could be reached” and connection refused to 127.0.0.1:53 (functions.exec_shell).\n- Connectivity to the dns_server IP is fine:\n  - ICMP from hosts to 10.200.0.2 successful with low RTT (functions.get_reachability).\n\nAssessment of anomalies\n- Abnormal behavior:\n  - DNS failures for local zone names (e.g., web0.local, web99.local) across the network.\n- Normal behavior:\n  - OSPF adjacency across core/distribution/server access is healthy.\n  - Routing tables correct and stable.\n  - DHCP successfully assigns addresses and default gateways to hosts.\n  - HTTP servers and load balancer reachable and return HTTP 200 when addressed by IP.\n  - Backend network is not advertised to hosts (as intended).\n\nFault localization\n- Single point localization: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\n  - Evidence: No port 53 listening; local DNS queries fail on the DNS server itself; clients point at this server and cannot resolve names.\n\nRoot cause hypothesis\n- DNS daemon on dns_server is not running or not bound to any interface (neither 127.0.0.1 nor 10.200.0.2). This results in a DNS outage for the local zone, preventing resolution of service FQDNs such as web0.local and web99.local.\n\nImpact\n- All FQDN-based access to local services (web servers and the load balancer) fails from user hosts, despite healthy IP connectivity and application servers. Users can only access services by IP, not by hostname.\n\nNo remediation is provided per request.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11549, "output_tokens": 4860, "total_tokens": 16409, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9472}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3648}}}
